Quickstart
Building a URI to query the National Statistical API begins with four basic requirements.

⓵ All requests start with this base URI.

https://api3.natst.at/

⓶ The first path parameter is a valid API key. A key contains 11 characters (four alphanumeric characters, a dash, then six alphanumeric characters). The account's API key can be found on the National Statistical account page (requires login) in the NatStat API navigation tab, or under Analysis Tools > NatStat API > Query Builder on any of the 29 service subsites.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/

⓷ The second path parameter is a valid endpoint. The available endpoints are boxscores, dataststus, elo, forecasts, games, glossary, lineups, moneyline, news, officials, overunder, pitchfx, playbyplay, playerperfs, players, pointspread, season, simulations, stats, teamperfs, teams, transactions, venues, winprob, teamcodes, leaguecodes. (Please note that not all sports return data for each endpoint.)

More information on endpoints and full methods can be found at the endpoint reference.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/games/

⓸ The third path parameter is one of the 29 sport data service codes (case-insensitive). A glossary of codes can be found below.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/games/nba/

⓹ The fourth (optional) path parameter is a "range" that limits the scope of returned data.

Season: The four-digit year of the date when the season ends. The default is the current season.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/games/milb/2025

Date(s): In YYYY-MM-DD format. Supplying two dates will return an inclusive range of results.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/pointspread/kbo/2025-04-12

Code: A non case-sensitive team, player or league code. A full list of team codes can be retrieved at the /teamcodes endpoint. A full list of team codes can be retrieved at the /leaguecodes endpoint. Player codes can be retrieved at the /players endpoint.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/games/fc/eng-pre

Data Format: Data from the National Statistical API is available in three different formats. Users can specify which format to return with the format query parameter. If no data format is specified, the API will send JSON-formatted data by default.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/venues/wnba/xml

The comma-separated and tab-separated (CSV/TSV) options were removed in API v2, as they are unable to handle multi-dimensional array objects. The Excel option was removed in API v2. If you require spreadsheet-formatted data, please review Analysis Tools > Data Exports from any of the 29 subsites' navigation menus.

json	JavaScript Object Notation (default)
xml	Extensible Markup Language
php	PHP SimpleXML Object
Search Term: If a comma-separated value is not matched with any of the above data types, the API will assume that it is a search term. The system will only accept the first entry in a comma-separated string as a search term.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/players/nba/curry

Values may be used in combination to further refine a search.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/games/mlb/2024-05-09,2024-05-15,bos

⓺ A fifth (optional) path parameter is a paginated "offset" number for recordsets. The default is 0, the beginning of the recordset.

https://api3.natst.at/xxxx-xxxxxx/seasons/nba/_/100

Changes in v3.5
In addition to over 150 minor updates, upgrades, adjustments and bug removals, API v3.5 contains important differences from the original API v3 that was launched in May 2024.

• The events endpoint has been added for all services. A query to this endpoint will return important real-time, in-game events in reverse chronological order. (Baseball: scoring plays; Basketball: runs, late lead changes, 30/40/50+ point games; Hockey: goals; Soccer: goals; American Football: TD, FG, turnovers.) This feed only contains events from the past 24 hours. For more events and advanced filtering functions, please consider the Interstat API.

• The projline endpoint has been added for all basketball, baseball, hockey and soccer data services. A query to this endpoint will return projected player statlines for all of today's games within the specified competition level.

• The Multiple IP Policy has been updated and clarified.

• NatStat's API servers in Northern Virginia, Frankfurt and Tokyo have been significantly upgraded for faster and smoother processing of user requests.

• API search-string functions have been improved or overhauled.

Migrating From v2
• API v3 utilizes the same simplified query structure as the premium Interstat API, making it easier than ever to write queries on the fly and make the most of hourly rate limits.

• Three endpoints from API v2 have been fully depreciated and are not included in API v3: rpi, social, tweets.

• The universal use of the term id has been discontinued in API v3. The term code indicates use with another endpoint: for example, GSW as a team code for Golden State Warriors, 15125 as a venue code for Chase Center, or 826 as a player code for Stephen Curry. The term id now implies a unique identifier for a data record.

• The max_results query parameter has been phased out. All queries return a maximum of 100 records, except for events, playbyplay, pitchfx, teamcodes, leaguecodes (500 records).

• All returned parameters are now in lowercase.

• Please test any queries and attempt alternate formats to view any applicable errors or status messages before contacting support.

Query Builder
National Statistical provides an interactive web application to assist with the creation and testing of valid URIs.

Access the Query Builder(s) that you are authorized to use under NatStat API on this page's navigation menu, or from any of the 29 service subsites under Analysis Tools > NatStat API > Query Builder.

You can easily and quickly regenerate your API key with the link at the top of the screen. The number in the upper right corner is the number of API calls you have remaining for the current hour (:00 to :59), and the number of minutes before your rate limit resets.

Create a URI with the text fields and pulldown menus, based on the displayed query parameters. Test the query by clicking Execute API Call. Copy the URI or the query output to your clipboard with one click. There is also an open-text field for team and player ID lookups.

